segments.text: I've always been a leader from my contemporaries, except two years at A&M.
I can't remember any leadership I did there.

Okay, now of course you were in the military for three decades, and I was wondering, you must have met a lot of officers who were A&M graduates, and a lot of officers who were West Point graduates, and some were ROTC men.
And I was wondering if you could tell me the difference between those types.
Well, I found quite a bit of difference when I was a flying instructor and in charge of primary flying stage at Brooks Field.
I found that the
young man who came from ROTC, A&M, Georgia Tech, and various other places, took to flying better than the graduates of West Point.
And I figured it out, it was because
Their mind hadn't been grooved along a certain line like they do at West Point at that time back in the 20's.
I think the West Point cadets were more or less put in a rut if you can put a youngster in a rut like that early in their thinking.
It made it a little more difficult for them to learn to fly than the A&M cadets and ROTC from the other universities.
I never noticed any difference between A&M cadets and Georgia Tech, for instance, or the various other ROTC units.
Do you think that any of them officers, when they became officers, do you think that they were well trained?
Yes, I think they were, I think they were as good as West Point officers.
Better in some respects, possibly not quite as good as others, but
I couldn't point out the differences and then of course each one is an individual and you can't classify a bunch of people because everyone's different.
But I was very proud of the A&M officers that I had under me and I knew
I was always proud of A&M.
Had a reputation throughout the Army of turning out fine officers.
I had some of them as cadets.
George Epright lived over there by Austin, was one of my students.
He came from A&M.
He's since given A&M a very large donation of land out of the land.
He was probably the best student I ever had.
He was from A&M.
Best flying student.
When you were at A&M, would you consider yourself an average student?
As far as students go, I was probably average.
talk to people about A&M, a number of them say that it's more than just a college, more than just an institution, but there's something special.
Would you agree with that, or what are your thoughts on that?
I think there's something special about Texas A&M that just breeds better class of citizens, better army officers, better big civil life.
There's something about the atmosphere there that, among the core, of course, it stressed discipline and integrity and honesty.
The other students now, I don't know much about.
The Corps is probably only about 10% of the, is it?
About 10% of them.
So I suppose that the other 90% are about the same as the Texas University.
I mean, they're the schools in Texas.
I think Texans are superior to them.
residents of any other state.
Why do you say that?
I think straighter, more patriotism.
Something about the Alamo law and something about Texas that makes you proud of it.
If you take pride in your state, then you can take pride in your country.
Were you sad when you left Texas A&M in 1917?
What's that?
Were you sad when you left A&M?
Did you want to come back?
Why did you leave?
Well, I left to help Dad on the ranch.
He couldn't hire anybody.
He was out there by himself.
And when I left, I had no idea what I was going to do, whether I was going to come back or not.
And the war had just started.
The war had just started, yeah.
And about August, I tried to enlist in the Marines, and they were pulled up, and that's why I put in this newfangledness of flying.
It would be a challenge to me.
So about four or five months later before I was able to get in.
Because they were killed too?
Were they killed?
Yeah, they didn't have any place.
They enlisted me, but I was on standby status until December.
I had a cousin who was a general in the army and I wrote him to see if he could.
He was a what?
A general?
Yeah, General Fletcher Sharp.
How'd you meet him?
Well, he was my cousin.
I wrote him.
capture a door in the Philippines with Wainwright.
He and Wainwright were in the same prison camp.
He uh, he wrote back.
I think maybe he helped me get in, and I finally got in in December.
Went to Austin to ground school.
I've got a letter here from...
I'll turn that light on.
There's two outlets there.
I don't know why she took them both.
I got it.
Okay.
I got a letter here from the United States Air Force, research on military leadership and it's written by Captain Puryear and this is back in 1961.
He asked certain questions here and I wrote the answers down.
Unfortunately, it didn't keep the question, but I think if you look at the answers I have here on leadership, it might give you some insight into my thinking on it.
Let's talk about your career.
Yeah.
And anything that, of course, you've written in your memoirs, which you're going to give us a copy of, anything that you've written,
You can just say that's in my memoirs and we can move on.
But otherwise, I would like to get an idea of your career.
Well, it's all written down in my memoirs.

1919, I was stationed at Carl Field, Wichita Falls, Texas, and an old schoolmate of mine, Bill Irwin, came through with a flying circus, and he wanted to know why I was still in the Army, why I couldn't get out and make a fortune flying in one of these, with his circus, taking up passengers, and they'd pay him so much for
or pairing at various functions.
So I decided I'd get out of the Army and be a barnstormer.
So I put in and I couldn't get out until October.
That's as soon as they let me loose of 1919 and by that time Bill Irwin had lost his life on the Dole flight.
trying to fly to Hawaii.
It was a $25,000 prize for the first one who flew from the mainland over to Hawaii.
And he was at the Blanca, I believe, in an airplane.
He started out with a mechanic and never was heard from again.
There I was out of the Army and no job, but that didn't bother me any.
I went down to Dallas, stayed with some friends there, and a fella hired me to buy an airplane for him.
He wanted to go out and take up passengers, a $10 ride, wanted me to fly a plane.
that's all covered in the memoirs.
Well, I was wondering about World War I and about your training.

Oh, well after eight weeks at ground school in Austin, Texas, there was no Vegans in the flying school for us, so they sent us all to Camp Deck at Dallas, Texas, which was in the fairgrounds at Dallas.
We were quartered in the
in the building that normally housed the animals, waiting vacancies in flying school.
And I've got that all covered in my memoirs.
In my flying school, I went to Kelly, and I went over to Brookston to take an instructor's course.
I went out to Georgia to be an instructor, a flying instructor.
How good was the quality of instruction when they taught you how to fly?
It was exceptionally good at Kelly.
At that time, I started April 6, 1918, and we had the old Jennys, JN-4Ds, Curtis JN-4Ds, and I had a man named Chandler who was my instructor for a duo.
I think he was a very fine instructor, and I think the quality of instruction was very good.
Were there any fatalities, any problems?
Well, a lot of cadets were killed, some instructors.
I had Eddie Stinson, who was a well-known aviator at that time.
He was an instructor at Kelly.
Joe Levery died recently.
I lived in San Antonio.
He was an acrobatic instructor.
I had the cream of the crop as far as instructors go.
What was the feeling?
Was the feeling that you were in a brand new field now?
Was it exciting?
Do you remember?
Well, I just remember I liked it.
I loved it.
It was exciting.
I'm not philosophical about it in any way that I can remember.
What did the other parts of the Army think about the Army Air Corps?
Well, they were jealous of us.
We wore white ribbons around our hats.
You had these old campaign hats, you know, stick out and come to a point up here.
And around the sweatband,
We wore white ribbon to denote that we were cadets.
We weren't enlisted men, we were cadets getting $75 a month.
Enlisted men were getting $13, I think, maybe $20.
We'd all go into town in San Antonio and meet the girls.
So and so would say, well, tell the girls at that white hat band that we had venereal disease.
And jealousy.
But I think that's pretty well covered.
And what campaigns, just briefly, what campaigns are, did you go, did they send you to France, or did you remain an instructor?

No, they kept me in this country as an instructor, and I think if the war had lasted another year, I would have probably been stuck right in the United States as a flying instructor because I was very good at it, and that was the first day I went out to Southern Field.
I was put in charge of a
small group, I don't know why they picked me, but they did, to teach them what they would get when they got to Brooks Field and they were going to take the instructor's course.
So that was the first day I was out there.
I flew eight hours instructing these
young lieutenants on what they were going to get when they got to Brooks Field.
I started my leadership right there.
But for the next, I didn't get in a position of leadership until
I guess in 1926, when I was picked to be the head man at the primary flying stage at Brooks Field.
I had 21 instructors and 120 students under my command.
That was my first big...
Okay, but before we get there, why'd you decide to quit barnstorming?
and when did you, and why did you decide to go back?
Okay, so you got out of the service in 1919, and then you barnstormed, and how long did you do that, and why did you decide to go back in?
Well, I gave up on this joker that hired me in Dallas.
I gave up on him because I didn't like him, and we weren't making any money, and so I quit him after about a month.
and I went back up to Dalhart to be with my folks for Christmas.
And then I got a call from Amarillo, a fella I'd known at the Caulfield, and said, we want you down here in our new flying company.
We're going to barnstorm all over the Panhandle.
We got two airplanes.
So I went down there and I was in the barnstorming business until
about April and May.
In the meantime, the War Department had written me a letter and went to Dalhart and my mother opened it.
April and May of what year?
And that's covered in my memoir.
Sure.
My mother called me up from Dalhart and said, son, there's a letter here from the War Department.
They want you back in the Army.
They would make you a first lieutenant.
If you must fly, son, why don't you get back in the Army where you can fly some decent equipment instead of those old crates that you're flying down there on an armarella?"
I said, okay mother.
So I accepted it.
I got back in the Army in September 1920.
I ordered the Brooksfield and I went right
restructuring again.
In 22 we moved up to Kelly and had an instructor there.
Then on the 1923 bombing of the battleships in New Jersey and West Virginia.
Yeah, tell me about that.
Well, I've got all that covered in detail in my memoirs.
Billy Mitchell.
Sure.
Did you have an opportunity to meet Billy Mitchell?
Yeah, he was a good friend of mine.
Could you characterize him?
What was he like?
Well, he was a very dynamic man.
On the order of MacArthur and Patton.
lots of physical and nervous energy and all.
He was always in trouble with the General Staff in Washington.
He was bound and determined that they were going to recognize the Air Corps as being a very valuable part of the Army and that the Air Corps could sink battleships
do this and that.
They didn't like him in Washington at all.
Of course, they tried him later.
This is being subordinated.
Anyway.
What'd you think of him?
I liked him.
Why?
Well, I liked him.
He was my type of man.
He was very much in love with flying and the Air Corps.
We called ourselves at that time.
He would stand up and tell these superior officers of his in Washington what he thought.
That's the way I always operated.
I just liked him at the time.
He liked me.
During his battleship bombing, one day he said, Beverly, take up a supercharged Martin bomber and see what the absolute ceiling is, how high it can get loaded, fully loaded.
So I had it loaded up and went up for an altitude test.
Well, he picked me for that.
Then during the bombing when there was one battleship still afloat he said, Beverly take your crew and go up and sink that battleship.
He picked me out of all the crews there.
So he seemed to like me.
And did you sink it?
Yeah.
My bomber put one 1100 pound bomb right down the smokestack from 11,000 feet.
He was a good bomber.
We had the old fashioned Navy bomb sites.
Now of course the Northern bomb sites come in since then.
I don't know what they're using now.
I'm so out of date with the Air Force that I don't know what kind of bomb sites they have now but that old Navy bomb site was very crude compared to what we use now.
How did you feel when you sang it?
Oh, I was elated of course.
Then we had this big critique, everybody in there you know.
Mitchell was going over what was happening and this and that and then I sent my best crew up to finish off the last ship.
Of course that made Captain Ross Cole and myself feel pretty good.
He was my bomber.
Were you a captain at that time?
Had you been promoted to captain then?
No, no.
We were all on a single promotion list until the mid-thirties.
The only way you moved up a file was somebody would either retire or die, but it was ahead of you.
So it was 1934 before I moved up to captain.
The promotions during the 1920s and the 1930s were extraordinarily slow.
Was that demoralizing?
No.
Everybody else was a lieutenant.
All my friends and contemporaries were lieutenants, except at every base they had one or two majors, you know, maybe a lieutenant colonel.
The rest were all lieutenants, so it didn't bother us.
We were getting enough money to live on and we lived in old shacks there at Kelly Field that had been built during 1917 and converted into living quarters for families.
But everybody else was living the same way so we never worried about money or the kind of quarters we were having.
getting things that seem to worry him so much today.
I don't understand it because it didn't bother us any.
Well why do you think it bothers him today?
I mean what's the difference?
I can't understand it.
What's the difference between an officer today and an officer back in the 1920s?
I think we were back in those days where we were in a new game.
We were felt ourselves to be superior to
ordinary humans and Americans and today it seems like they think more they're less patriotic and think more about money and promotion and prestige rank
Why is their crime rate so much worse today than it was back in those days?
I don't know.
But you don't know why this has changed now, in the officer court?
Yeah, I've got lots of good friends out here at the base at Laughlin, and the colonels out there are getting a lot more money than I'm drawing,
retired, but there seem to be a lot of them seem to be wanting more money.
Some of them get out and go to flying for the airlines, $40,000 and $50,000.
$40,000 is starter pay and the chance to go up to $75,000.
Well, I guess you can't blame them much when that opportunity wasn't there when I was coming up.
There were no airlines that they were asking me to get out and fly for them.
Did you ever think during the 1920's or the 30's that you should get out to fly for the mail or something like the U.S. Mail or something like that?
No, no.
I was very happy where I was.
but then fly that dirty whip.
We did fly it.
We tried to fly the mail when Franklin Roosevelt canceled all air mail contracts and told Benny Filloy, who was chief of the Air Force, to fly the air mail.
We weren't equipped for it.
We'd been on starvation rations since
When the Depression started in 1929, we had no very poor equipment for flying air and mail.
We had no radio aids for night flying, bad weather flying, and we made a mess of it.
We lost twelve, I think it was, little fine pilots.
plus the airplanes that they ran.
In 1927, Lindbergh crossed the Atlantic.
Did you ever, what did you think about that?
Well, I thought that, I wondered if I could stay awake thirty-six hours and do that.
I didn't think I could.
I thought I must have tremendous physical
energy to keep awake that long.
I just didn't think I could have done it in time.
I'm happy to see him do it.
Did you know anybody that also wanted to try to do it?
Did you know any of your colleagues or yourself ever think about trying to find the Atlantic?
No.
I can't swim.
Did you ever have an opportunity to meet Lundberg?
Yeah.
When was that?
He and his wife.
That was in 1929.
I was up in Kansas City at Chargent.
flying for our global flying school.
I was on leave from the Air Force.
He was taking the airplane out and he stopped and shook hands with me and his wife Ann.
That's the only time I met him.
Did you have an opportunity to talk to him?
No.
Now tell me about this 1926 you said that you ordered.
Was that your, given your, was it your first command then?
Uh, I see.
In charge of 120 pilots was it?
120 pilots and 21 instructors, yeah.
Yeah, that was my first command.
I loved it.
I would assign the students to various instructors and if the instructor decided the student wasn't qualified to be a pilot, I'd give him a check ride to verify it.
Also, I gave a check ride to all the students when they graduated and moved over to Kelly for the training.
So I spent quite a lot of time checking students for washout and for promotion.
Were there a number, a large number of students that didn't make it?
Yes, a large number.
I would say half of them didn't make it.
One just lacked the natural ability to
coordination of mind and muscle, and judgment of speed and distance, the temperament, various things that go to make a first class, at the time, army pilot.
And I'd be surprised how many of them don't have that.
Nowadays, it seems to me like they don't wash out quite as many.
At that time, we were flying, what you might say, by the seat of our britches.
We had no instruments to speak of, no radio aids, and it was strictly contact flying, and you had to be very alert and have all of these qualities
some of which are not required today because it seemed like they fly by push button a goody of the day.
So, I would say I don't think the washout rate out here at Laughlin, which is the primary flying school, is anywhere near like it was with us.
I expect it's more like 25%, maybe less than that.
And another thing out here now, they have a simulator that you get in and it's built so that you're sitting there operating in this simulator and you're actually
You look like you're flying a plane.
You may know something about those.
They use it also in the handling of ships, sea, things like that, simulators.
And they get a lot of simulator training before they ever get in an airplane.
And I think it helps them a great deal.
It certainly saves the government millions of dollars in money.
Why do you say that you liked that command very much?
Why did I say what?
That you liked your command so much, your first one in 1926.
Oh, I just liked it.
I liked to be the top man.
I like to direct people.
I think I've got the ability.
I know I have the judgment.
I'm a natural born teacher.
I like to teach.
When I retired from the Air Force, I tried to get a job as a teacher, and they said I was too old.
But I like to teach youngsters.
great deal of satisfaction in turning out a good flyer, for instance.
I'm very proud of the ones that I turned out.
And how long did you stay?
And where was this?
This is Brooksfield, San Antonio.
Okay, and how long did you?
I was there two years, and I moved over to Kelly.
I wanted to
I was playing polo with the Kelly Field Polo Team and I wanted to get over there closer to where the horses were.
In 1928 I requested transfer to Kelly from Brooks and it was approved.
I went over to Kelly and his instructor for one class in the attack section.
And I was put in charge of the section in the next class.
And I was close to the polo stables.
And I'd have to know that, work out horses, practice polo, magic play golf.
We worked from seven till about one, three for the day.
So why such a short day?
Well, he worked from 7 to 1 flying and that's not a short day.
Oh, no.
Okay.
That's not a short day by any means with students.
Actually, three hours when I was in charge over at Brooks.
I figured an instructor could do a good job for three hours and that's about all.
He had six students, each one got 30 minutes of dual instruction each day.
Later on one or two of them washed out while you could give more time to the others.
But three hours, about a day's work as a flying instructor.
You'd be surprised what it takes out of you.
Were you a good bullet player?
I had a national rating of two goals.
Really?
And where'd you pick up the polo?
Kelly, Kelly Field.
We had a major garrison at Kelly in 1921.
In 1922, a very fine fella, he decided that Air Force ought to have a polo team.
He went over to Fort Sam Houston and borrowed horses, built stables at Kelly, bought hay and so forth for her.
And he started a polo squad there.
And I went down there in 1922 from Post Field, Oklahoma.
I started playing polo.
I'd already, I knew how to ride a horse.
I'd been on a ranch quite a bit.
And I loved the polo.
That's the greatest outdoor game with any of them.
Was the Army Air Force abducted by the Depression?
Well, we were cut out on a number of airplanes they bought for us.
We were cut out on the amount of flying we could do because we couldn't pay for the gasoline.
They gave us all a one month furlough, a payless furlough.
cut out on the amount of money it took for salaries, and we, by the way, got that back later on.
Congress reinstated it, but we spent a month there without pay, everybody in the Army.
That was 1930 and 31, 1930 I believe.
My wife and I just went to Mexico City and spent the month in Mexico City.
Why'd you decide to go down?
We'd been studying Spanish in San Antonio with Senorita Oviedo Gonzalez there.
I just wanted to learn Spanish.
So did you down in Mexico City?
She said, I've got some friends in Mexico City and I'll fix it up so you live right with them.
That way you can learn.

the language quicker, so she fixed it up with friends of hers in Mexico City to meet us at the train, take us to their home, and we lived there with them about a week and decided it was too confining and moved to a hotel.
But we enjoyed the month down there very much.
Didn't learn much Spanish, but we had a good time.
Did the status of the Army Air Force change when Franklin Roosevelt was elected?
Did you get more money and equipment?
Let me see.
We started getting more equipment in 1933.
I was at the Air Corps Tactical School.
And we were getting a little more money for airplanes, but not very much.
We tried to fly the airmail in 1934 and made a botch of it because of lack of equipment.
instruments and so forth.
And that helped us get increased appropriations in 1934 and 35.
We started getting some modern equipment.
About the time we got the Martin B-10 bomber, it was the first airplane we got where the
landing gear folded up.
Retractable gear.
Was it a single wing?
It was a single wing, low wing, and two engines.
A friend of mine, like Duffy, led a flight from Miami to Panama.
I was down in Panama in 1935 when he came in there.
I got a picture
Duffy and General Brett and the other basic commander and so forth.
I've got a lot of clippings and pictures in there that you can... How long are you going to be here?
I don't know how long it will take.
I was going to say, you can take them back tonight and bring them back in the morning.
You might look them over.
And also this...
I got a copy of my manuscript.
Let me look that over.
What was your command after you left?
What was your command in the 1930s?

Well, after I finished school at Montgomery, Alabama, that was a nine months course in air corps tactics, I was sent to the Boston airport to be commanding, be instructor for the Massachusetts National Guard squadron there.
And I despised that work.
Why?
It had nothing to do.
They have a good going outfit up there.
They didn't need me as an instructor.
I didn't know any more about the observation than they did.
They were an observation squadron.
But every squadron had to have a regular Army instructor.
So I was hooked for that job and I kept trying to get out of it.
temporary duty down at Langley Field, Virginia as a student in celestial navigation.
Well, that took up about six weeks.
And then they decided I ought to stay there as an instructor in the next course.
Well, that suited me fine.
Anything rather than go back to that National Guard squadron.
So I stayed down at Langley as instructor in the navigation for the next course.

and that went through Christmas and then about January I think Roosevelt canceled air and mail contracts with civilian airlines and told the Air Corps to fly the air and mail and I was up at Floyd Bennett Airport there right outside New York City
to bring an airplane up there.
Major Jones, who was in charge of airmail for that area, said, get on the train, go to Pittsburgh as a control officer.
Stop the killing out there.
I think they'd lost something like five or six airplanes just on that one route.
